text: Before transmitting live filings, software developers must pass testing procedures.  For more
label: BODY

text: information on testing procedures, see Publication EFAST-A, User’s Guide for
label: BODY

text: Electronic/Magnetic Media Filing of Forms 5500 and 5500-EZ.
label: BODY

text: Each transmission consists of a single or multiple batches of filings. A transmission may be sent
label: BODY

text: via modem-to-modem or via magnetic media. There is no limit to the number of batches that can
label: BODY

text: be sent for each transmission. For detailed modem-to-modem and magnetic media specifications,
label: BODY

text: A batch consists of a single or multiple filings. Each batch can contain up to 1,000 filings.
label: BODY

text: Transmissions must consist of only complete batches, and these batches must be transmitted in
label: BODY

text: their entirety sequentially. That is, the first batch must be completely transmitted before the next
label: BODY

text: batch begins. Figure 1, on the next page, shows the relationship between transmissions and
label: BODY

text: EFAST-B, Part I  Draft Electronic Filing Specification (DEL 1022) 18 September 2008
label: BODY

text: A batch consists of two or three different types of files: .DOL Files, Unstructured Attachment
label: BODY

text: The .DOL file contains the information from the official forms and schedules (which are Form
label: BODY

text: 5500, Form 5500-EZ, Schedule A, Schedule C, Schedule D, Schedule E, Schedule G, Schedule
label: BODY

text: H, Schedule I, Schedule R, and Schedule SSA).  It also contains Unstructured Text Records,
label: BODY

text: which are unstructured attachments submitted within the .DOL file (see Section 5.7.6).
label: BODY

text: The Unstructured Attachment Files are files containing information that is not contained on the
label: BODY

text: official forms. Examples of unstructured attachments that must be contained in separate files
label: BODY

text: include Schedule H Accountant’s Opinions and Schedules MB and SB Actuarial Attachments,
label: BODY

text: and images of Schedules MB and SB. Please see Section 6 for more information on unstructured
label: BODY

text: attachments.  Images of pages for Schedules MB and SB must be included as unstructured filing
label: BODY

text: The .RDY file is transmitted after the .DOL file and the Unstructured Attachment Files for
label: BODY

text: modem-to-modem batches only.  It has the same filename as the .DOL file, except it has an
label: BODY

text: “.RDY” extension.  This file lets the EFAST modem-to-modem processing system know when
label: BODY

text: the entire batch is completely transmitted and ready to be processed.  Only modem-to-modem
label: BODY

text: filers should transmit this file.  See Section 11 for more details.
label: BODY

text: The .DOL file can contain the information for up to 1,000 different filings. There can be up to
label: BODY

text: 4,095 separate unstructured attachment files attached to this .DOL file.  These unstructured
label: BODY

text: attachment files can belong to any of the filings that the .DOL file contains. That is, the
label: BODY

text: unstructured attachment files in a batch do not necessarily have to be attached to the same filing.
label: BODY

text: EFAST-B, Part I  Draft Electronic Filing Specification (DEL 1022) 18 September 2008
label: BODY

text: The entire .DOL filename must not exceed 30 characters (the dot and the extension not included)
label: BODY

text: and must have “.DOL” as its extension. A transmitter should never submit a .DOL file that has
label: BODY

text: the same filename as a previously transmitted .DOL file.  That is, for each EFIN, all .DOL files
label: BODY

text: If .DOL files are not named uniquely, there is a possibility that data could be overwritten.  Also,
label: BODY

text: the name of the .DOL file is used as identification in the initial electronic acknowledgements.
label: BODY

text: Note: Even an amended file’s filename must be unique.  The filename is not used to identify
label: BODY

text: amended filings, so please verify that the amended check box on the first page of Form 5500
label: BODY

text: (field B(2)) or Form 5500-EZ (field A(2))is selected if submitting an amended filing.
label: BODY

text: The .DOL file must be an ASCII text file.
label: BODY

text: Each record within a transmission must be preceded by two four-byte fields. The first four-byte
label: BODY

text: field is the Byte Count for the record. This byte count contains a count of the number of bytes
label: BODY

text: within the record including the four bytes for the counter itself, four bytes for the Record
label: BODY

text: Beginning Mark (****), and one byte for the Record Terminus Character (#). The second four-
label: BODY

text: byte field is the Record Beginning Mark, which must be four asterisks (****).
label: BODY

text: Every record must have the Record Terminus Character (#) as its last byte.
label: BODY

text: A .DOL file consists of a variable number of fixed length and variable length records. The size
label: BODY

text: and format of the record for each page of each form and schedule are specified in Part II Record
label: BODY

text: No page of a schedule or form should be generated if there are no entries on that page record. A
label: BODY

text: blank page (Record ID only) may cause the filing to be deemed non-acceptable, except in cases
label: BODY

text: where a form requires that one page be present when the other page is present.
label: BODY

text: Page one of Form 5500 or of Form 5500-EZ must have a record present. For the Schedules, only
label: BODY

text: the pages (in the proper sequence) which contain significant data must have a record present.
label: BODY

text: If page 2 and/or any succeeding page of any schedule contains significant data, page 1 of that
label: BODY

text: schedule must also be present and must contain significant data.
label: BODY

text: 5.3 Types of Records in the .DOL File
label: HH1

text: A .DOL file consists of a TRANS Record, the Encryption Record (if applicable), the Filings,
label: BODY

text: The Filings consist of a single Header Record, all Filing Records (one for each page of the
label: BODY

text: 5500 or 5500-EZ), Schedule Records (one for each page of each schedule), Unstructured
label: BODY

text: Attachment Indicator Records (one for each file attached to the filing), Unstructured Text
label: BODY

text: EFAST-B, Part I  Draft Electronic Filing Specification (DEL 1022) 18 September 2008
label: BODY

text: Records (one for each textual attachment submitted inside the DOL file), and a single Summary
label: BODY

text: There should be no spaces, carriage returns, or any other characters between records in a .DOL
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY
